{"_path":"/articles/frontend-system-design-2-1","_dir":"articles","_draft":false,"_partial":false,"_locale":"","title":"What is short polling? Learn with example","description":"Dive into short polling methodologies. Explore the technique of frequent requests to servers at fixed intervals, enabling frontend applications to obtain recent data updates for dynamic content.","slidesUrl":"https://github.com/AherRahul/portfolio-v1/blob/main/content/articles","dateModified":"2025-03-01","datePublished":"2025-03-01","showOnArticles":false,"courseName":"02-frontend-system-design","topics":["nodejs","javascript"],"readingTime":{"text":"4 min read","minutes":3.23,"time":193800,"words":646},"body":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"img","props":{"alt":"image.png","src":"https://res.cloudinary.com/duojkrgue/image/upload/v1744108647/Portfolio/FrontendSystemDesignCourse/6_llcndo.png"},"children":[]}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Ah, I see! Let‚Äôs imagine this scenario: You‚Äôre super hungry, but the kitchen is closed. You can‚Äôt just go in and make something yourself, so you‚Äôve ordered food, but you‚Äôre not sure when it‚Äôll be ready. What do you do? You can‚Äôt wait forever, so you keep knocking on the kitchen door at regular intervals, hoping to see if your food is ready yet."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Every few seconds, you knock again, checking if it‚Äôs time to eat. It‚Äôs not constant‚Äîjust a brief check, then you wait and knock again after a short while. This is exactly like short polling. You keep checking for an update (your food being ready) at small intervals, without establishing a long connection, just knocking (or requesting) repeatedly until you get the response."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In short polling, just like you keep knocking, the system repeatedly asks for data at regular intervals, waiting for a response each time."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So, here we are going to discuss short polling, including its interview perspective with examples and code. So, let's not wait anymore and start learning."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"It is a methodology we generally use to connect the front end to the backend‚Äîa communication technique."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Generally, when we need data, the front end calls an API and uses it. If you need data again, you call the API, and it provides the data after each request."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"img","props":{"alt":"image.png","src":"https://heyashu.in/images/blogs/sp_2.png"},"children":[]}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"But what if you need this data quickly, like loading a cricket score, checking notifications from the backend, or seeing if the delivery boy has arrived? This is called the short polling technique, where you repeatedly call or check for results in real-time and need constant updates."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"It is not a persistent connection but retrieves data after each call. We are not increasing or establishing a new connection over an existing one. Instead, we call the API each time, but the calling frequency is very high, happening again and again."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"img","props":{"alt":"image.png","src":"https://heyashu.in/images/blogs/sp_3.png"},"children":[]}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So, to check real-time data, you can use short polling. But remember, calling an API repeatedly is not scalable. If the API has limited reso